explanation:
- OS_BinSemFlush_Impl (declaration/definition): The target passes &token into OS_BinSemFlush_Impl. To decide if the pointer parameter should be const-qualified (MISRA rule), the prototype and/or implementation of OS_BinSemFlush_Impl must be inspected to see whether it modifies the token or only reads it. If it does not modify the token, its parameter should be declared as pointer-to-const.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById (declaration): OS_BinSemFlush calls OS_ObjectIdGetById(&token) prior to calling the Impl function; this call likely writes/initializes token. Knowing its signature (whether it requires a non-const OS_object_token_t*) is necessary to determine whether token must be non-const throughout the function or can be made const for later use.
- OS_object_token_t (typedef/definition): The actual type of token (struct, pointer, etc.) affects whether making a pointer-to-const is meaningful and what members might be modified. The typedef/definition is needed to determine the correct const placement and whether members are mutated by callees.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken (declaration): Called inside OS_BinSemFlush_Impl (per the call graph). Knowing whether this function takes a pointer-to-const or modifies the token helps determine whether OS_BinSemFlush_Impl (and thus the pointer passed from OS_BinSemFlush) can be const-qualified.
- OS_Posix_BinSemAcquireMutex (declaration): Also called by OS_BinSemFlush_Impl. Its parameter constness/usage can indicate whether the token is modified within the Impl path; this affects whether the token pointer could/should be const-qualified.

(These symbols provide the minimal type and prototype information needed to determine if the pointer passed into and through these calls is modified and therefore whether const-qualification is required/possible under the MISRA rule.)
